│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                            │
│                                                                                        │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                        │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                            │
│ The crash occurs due to an assertion failure in                                        │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF():                                             │
│   assert(hasPlanWithVF(ScalarVF) && "More than a single plan/VF w/o any plan having    │
│ scalar VF");                                                                           │
│ This asserts that when there is more than a single plan/VF, there must be at least one │
│ VPlan with scalar VF (VF=1). In the provided reproducer, VPlans contains multiple      │
│ plans/VFs but none with scalar VF, leading to the assertion failure and abort.         │
│                                                                                        │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                                │
│ The opt log shows SE analysis and a trip count. The pass crashes immediately upon      │
│ attempting to compute the best VF. The relevant source context shows computeBestVF     │
│ special-cases the trivial case of a single plan with a single VF, but otherwise it     │
│ requires that there exists a scalar VF plan. The log confirms the failure occurs at    │
│ that assertion in computeBestVF.                                                       │
│ Additionally, buildVPlansWithVPRecipes is called with scalar MinVF (lines 7170-7171),  │
│ but tryToBuildVPlanWithVPRecipes can return plans that do not have scalar VF. There is │
│ code that truncates minimal bitwidths only if the plan does not have scalar VF         │
│ (8750-8753), indicating plans without scalar VF are possible.                          │
│                                                                                        │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                                │
│ The planner can construct multiple VPlans without including a scalar VF plan,          │
│ particularly when widening is applicable only for VF>1 and the VPlan construction path │
│ skips or omits scalar VF variants. The assertion in computeBestVF assumes that if      │
│ there are multiple plans or VFs, a scalar plan must exist to serve as the baseline for │
│ cost comparisons. However, that invariant is not enforced by the plan building logic,  │
│ leading to the assertion failure.                                                      │
│ Given that CM.expectedCost(ScalarVF) is independently computed without requiring a     │
│ scalar VPlan, the planner can still operate and compare vector VFs against the scalar  │
│ baseline even if no scalar VPlan exists. Therefore, the assertion is overly strict     │
│ against the current plan-building behavior and causes a crash on valid inputs where    │
│ vector-only plans exist.                                                               │
│                                                                                        │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                             │
│ We should relax the assertion in computeBestVF to avoid crashing when multiple         │
│ plans/VFs exist with no scalar plan. Instead, proceed to compute ScalarCost using the  │
│ legacy cost model and continue evaluating vector VFs. This maintains correctness of    │
│ cost comparison and avoids the abort.                                                  │
│                                                                                        │
│ Edit:                                                                                  │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp                                │
│ - Lines: 7465-7467                                                                     │
│ - Change: Replace the assert with a defensive check that proceeds without a scalar     │
│ plan.                                                                                  │
│                                                                                        │
│ Suggested replacement:                                                                 │
│   ElementCount ScalarVF = ElementCount::getFixed(1);                                   │
│   // Proceed even if no plan has scalar VF; use legacy cost model for scalar baseline. │
│   // This can occur when VPlan construction creates only vector plans.                 │
│   // The scalar cost below is computed via CM.expectedCost(ScalarVF).                  │
│   // assert(hasPlanWithVF(ScalarVF) && "More than a single plan/VF w/o any plan having │
│ scalar VF");                                                                           │
│                                                                                        │
│ No other functional changes are needed, since the code already computes ScalarCost and │
│ uses it for comparisons.                                                               │
│                                                                                        │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                         │
│ The crash is due to an assertion that enforces an invariant not guaranteed by the      │
│ VPlan building pipeline: the presence of a scalar VF plan when multiple plans/VFs      │
│ exist. By relaxing the assertion and relying on the legacy cost model to compute the   │
│ scalar baseline cost, computeBestVF can proceed to select the best VF without          │
│ aborting. This fix preserves correctness and prevents the crash for the provided       │
│ reproducer and similar cases where only vector VPlans are constructed.                 │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                        │
